### **Partisan Asymmetry Analysis (H2)**

A one-way ANOVA test confirms a statistically significant difference in populist intensity between the two parties. Republican documents display a higher mean populist intensity (0.793) compared to Democratic documents (0.681).

| Party | Mean Populism Score | Mean Nationalism Score | Mean Populist Intensity Index |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Democrat | 0.704 | 0.628 | 0.681 |
| Republican | 0.790 | 0.800 | 0.793 |
| **ANOVA** | | | **F=8.71, p=0.005** ‚≠ê |

This gap is driven by higher scores on both axes. Republican rhetoric, as seen in the 2016 platform, emphasizes "American greatness" and exceptionalism [10], while Inaugural rhetoric from President Trump explicitly defined a conflict between "the people" and a failed "establishment" in Washington [1]. In contrast, Democratic documents, while employing populist framing around economic justice [11], often ground national identity in civic and inclusive terms, such as being a "nation of immigrants" [13].

### **Contextual Variance by Document Type (H6)**

The analysis confirms that the context of a speech significantly impacts its rhetorical style. State of the Union (SOTU) addresses, which often have a more partisan and policy-driven focus, are significantly more populist than Inaugural Addresses, which traditionally emphasize unity and institutional continuity.

| Document Type | Mean Populism Score | ANOVA vs. Inaugural (p-value) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Inaugural | 0.647 | - |
| SOTU | 0.758 | **0.026** ‚≠ê |

Evidence from President Biden's tenure clearly illustrates this divide. His 2021 Inaugural Address stressed institutional norms like the "peaceful transfer of power" [8], while his 2024 SOTU address adopted strong populist language about investing in "people that have been forgotten" [7]. This pattern is also visible in President Obama's addresses, where he used anti-elite framing like "Main Street isn't" rewarded while "Wall Street is" in a SOTU speech [9].

### **Correlation of Populism and Nationalism (H4)**

The hypothesis of decoupling events was rejected. The data reveals a strong positive correlation (Pearson's r = 0.73) between the populism-pluralism and nationalism-patriotism scores. This indicates that as rhetoric becomes more populist, it also tends to become more nationalist.

```mermaid
